0","Abt 1285":"omkring 1285","1315":"1315","about 1318":"omkring 1318","1368":"1368","1310":"1310","about 1315":"omkring 1315","1265":"1265","1320":"1320","4 January 1318":"4. januar 1318","1318":"1318","Scotland":"Skotland","Louden, Ayrshire, , Scotland":"Ayrshire, Skotland, United Kingdom","Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland":"Lochawe, Argyll, Skotland"},"nl":{"1286–4 January 1318":"1286–4 januari 1318","1286–1318":"1286–1318","1297–Female":"1297–Overleden","1310–1368":"1310–1368","1315–Male":"1315–Overleden","1318–Male":"1318–Overleden","1260–1320":"1260–1320","1265–Female":"1265–Overleden","1286":"1286","1297":"1297","1260":"1260","Abt 1285":"circa 1285","1315":"1315","about 1318":"circa 1318","1368":"1368","1310":"1310","about 1315":"circa 1315","1265":"1265","1320":"1320","4 January 1318":"4 januari 1318","1318":"1318","Scotland":"Schotland","Louden, Ayrshire, , Scotland":"Ayrshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland":"Lochawe, Argyll, Schotland"},"en":{"1286–4 January 1318":"1286–4 January 1318","1286–1318":"1286–1318","1297–Female":"1297–Deceased","1310–1368":"1310–1368","1315–Male":"1315–Deceased","1318–Male":"1318–Deceased","1260–1320":"1260–1320","1265–Female":"1265–Deceased","1286":"1286","1297":"1297","1260":"1260","Abt 1285":"about 1285","1315":"1315","about 1318":"about 1318","1368":"1368","1310":"1310","about 1315":"about 1315","1265":"1265","1320":"1320","4 January 1318":"4 January 1318","1318":"1318","Scotland":"Scotland","Louden, Ayrshire, , Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland":"Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Campbell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Camble","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campbel","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Cambell","meanings":["(1997: 229;2007: 1415; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campell","meanings":["(2007: 398; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire) and English: variant of   Campbell   (see also   Camel  )."]},{"name":"Beauchamp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."]},{"name":"Camel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Napoleon, Patrice.","English (of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Norman French <i>came(i)l</i> ‘camel’ (from Latin <i>camelus</i>, classical Greek <i>kamēlos</i>), possibly denoting a clumsy person or someone with long legs. It may also be a topographic or habitational name referring to a house with a sign depicting a camel (although surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English); compare 5 below.","English: possibly a habitational name from Queen Camel and West Camel in Somerset, early recorded as <i>Camel(le)</i>, possibly a Celtic name from <i>canto-</i> ‘border, district’ and <i>mēl</i> ‘bare hill’."]}]},{"name":"Duncan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Donnchadh , also used among people without Scottish connections. This was the name of a 7th-century Scottish saint (abbot of Iona) and two medieval kings of Scotland. The final ‐<i>n</i> in the Anglicized form seems to be the result of confusion with the Gaelic word <i>ceann</i> ‘head’ in the Latinized form <i>Duncanus</i>.  Compare Irish  Donagh ."],"variants":[{"name":"Donnchadh","meanings":["Gaelic: compound of Old Celtic <i>donn</i> ‘brown’ + <i>chadh</i> ‘chief’ or ‘noble’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Duncan Campbell - Nineth Lord of Loudoun was born in 1286, in Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland, his father, Donald Campbell Laird van Lochow en Benderloch, was 26 and his mother, Amabilla, was 21. He married Susanna Crauford of Loudoun in 1315, in Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died on 4 January 1318, in his hometown, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1286–4 January 1318":"1286–4. jaanuar 1318","1286–1318":"1286–1318","1297–Female":"1297–Surnud","1310–1368":"1310–1368","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1318–Male":"1318–Surnud","1260–1320":"1260–1320","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1286":"1286","1297":"1297","1260":"1260","Abt 1285":"umbes 1285","1315":"1315","about 1318":"umbes 1318","1368":"1368","1310":"1310","about 1315":"umbes 1315","1265":"1265","1320":"1320","4 January 1318":"4. jaanuar 1318","1318":"1318","Scotland":"Scotland","Louden, Ayrshire, , Scotland":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland":"Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland"},"fi":{"1286–4 January 1318":"1286–4. tammikuuta 1318","1286–1318":"1286–1318","1297–Female":"1297–Kuollut","1310–1368":"1310–1368","1315–Male":"1315–Kuollut","1318–Male":"1318–Kuollut","1260–1320":"12